8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1197, L.D. 1786, “An Act to Require
10 the Department of Environmental Protection to Provide Certain Information Regarding
11 Perfluoroalkyl and Polyfluoroalkyl Substances to the Public and Private Drinking Water
12 Well Owners”
13 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
14 following:
15 'Sec. 1. 22 MRSA §2660-Z is enacted to read:
16 §2660-Z. Information regarding PFAS; private drinking water wells
17 1. Definitions. As used in this section, unless the context otherwise indicates, the
18 following terms have the following meanings.
19 A. "Department" means the Department of Environmental Protection.
20 B. "Perfluoroalkyl and polyfluoroalkyl substances" or "PFAS" means a perfluoroalkyl
21 substance or polyfluoroalkyl substance that is detectable in drinking water using
22 standard laboratory methods established by the United States Environmental Protection
23 Agency, including regulated PFAS contaminants.
24 C. "Regulated PFAS contaminants" means:
25 (1) The specific PFAS compounds regulated pursuant to the drinking water
26 standards adopted by the Department of Health and Human Services in accordance
27 with Resolve 2021, chapter 82; or
28 (2) If maximum contaminant levels for PFAS are adopted by the Department of
29 Health and Human Services subsequent to the adoption of the drinking water
30 standards described in subparagraph (1), the specific PFAS compounds regulated
31 pursuant to those maximum contaminant levels.
32 2. Posting of information regarding maximum contaminant levels for PFAS. The
33 department shall post on its publicly accessible website information regarding the most
34 stringent maximum contaminant levels adopted by a federal agency or the State for
Page 1 - 132LR2311(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1197, L.D. 1786
315 regulated PFAS contaminants, measured in parts per trillion, that are in effect at the time
326 the information is posted and update the information whenever a maximum contaminant
337 level is changed.
4 3. Provision of information to owner of private drinking water well tested for
5 PFAS contamination. If the department conducts or facilitates the testing of a private
6 drinking water well for potential PFAS contamination, it shall provide to the owner of the
7 well, by mail and, if possible, by e-mail, the following information at the time that it
8 provides the owner with the results of that testing:
9 A. Information regarding the most stringent maximum contaminant levels adopted by
10 a federal agency or the State for regulated PFAS contaminants, measured in parts per
11 trillion, that are in effect at the time of the testing;
12 B. A comparison of the testing results to the most stringent maximum contaminant
13 levels adopted by a federal agency or the State for regulated PFAS contaminants,
14 measured in parts per trillion, that are in effect at the time of the testing; and
15 C. Information regarding resources available to owners of private drinking water wells
16 affected by PFAS contamination, including information regarding available mitigation
17 strategies for PFAS in private drinking water wells, information regarding entities that
18 test for PFAS in private drinking water wells and information regarding financial
19 assistance, if available, from state, federal and local governments and other sources to
20 support testing and mitigation of PFAS in private drinking water wells.
21 4. Provision of information to other private drinking water well owners. If the
22 department has not conducted or facilitated the testing of a private drinking water well for
23 potential PFAS contamination, the department shall provide to the owner of the private
24 drinking water well, by mail and, if possible, by e-mail, the information under subsection
25 3, paragraphs A and C if the department has knowledge that the well may be contaminated
26 by PFAS or if the owner requests such information by telephone, in writing or by e-mail.'
27 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
28 number to read consecutively.
29 SUMMARY
3300 This amendment replaces the bill. The amendment requires the Department of
3311 Environmental Protection to post on its publicly accessible website information regarding
3322 the current most stringent maximum contaminant levels adopted by a federal agency or the
3333 State for regulated PFAS contaminants, measured in parts per trillion. The amendment
3344 also requires that, if the department conducts or facilitates the testing of a private drinking
3355 water well for potential PFAS contamination, it must provide to the owner of the well, by
3366 mail and, if possible, by e-mail, at the time that it provides the owner with the results of
3377 that testing, information regarding maximum contaminant levels for regulated PFAS
3388 contaminants, a comparison of the testing results to those levels and information regarding
3399 resources available to owners of private drinking water wells affected by PFAS. The
4400 department is directed to provide similar information to other owners of private drinking
